{"parse":{"title":"Portraits of American Life Study","pageid":51486360,"revid":737487546,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>Portraits of American Life Study</b> (abbreviated <b>PALS</b>, originally known as the <b>Panel Study of American Religion and Ethnicity</b>) is a <a href=\"/wiki/Panel_study\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Panel study\">panel study</a> focusing on religion in the United States, particularly as it relates to racial and ethnic diversity. The study's first wave of data collection took place in 2006, and surveyed 2,610 people. In 2008, the researchers attempted re-contact with the 522 original respondents who attended religious services several times per year despite not being a member of a religious congregation.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The original 2006 study was led by sociologists Michael Emerson of <a href=\"/wiki/Rice_University\" title=\"Rice University\">Rice University</a> and David Sikkink of the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Notre_Dame\" title=\"University of Notre Dame\">University of Notre Dame</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> In 2012, the researchers surveyed exactly the same people they originally surveyed six years earlier. The 2012 survey showed that a significantly higher percent of Americans (58%) respected all religions equally than did in the original 2006 survey (one-third).<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> In 2016, <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Oklahoma\" title=\"University of Oklahoma\">University of Oklahoma</a> sociologist Samuel Perry analyzed data from the PALS and found that people who watch <a href=\"/wiki/Pornography\" title=\"Pornography\">pornography</a> at least once a week are more likely to be religious six years later.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> A 2013 <a href=\"/wiki/Brandeis_University\" title=\"Brandeis University\">Brandeis University</a> analysis of the PALS found that people who consider religion important in their lives are more likely to make decisions based on their religion.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Portraits_of_American_Life_Study&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.thearda.com/pals/about/overview.asp\">\"Portraits of American Life Study Overview\"</a>. <i>Association of Religion Data Archives</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">1 September</span> 2016</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Association+of+Religion+Data+Archives&amp;rft.atitle=Portraits+of+American+Life+Study+Overview&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.thearda.com%2Fpals%2Fabout%2Foverview.asp&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APortraits+of+American+Life+Study\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note